<paragraph blockId="40.[806,1422,1575,1903]" lastBlockId="41.[164,779,198,373]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="540" pageId="40" pageNumber="539">
<materialsCitation country="Madagascar" county="We" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="540" location="This" municipality="Ankarafantsika forest" pageId="40" pageNumber="539" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Mahajanga" typeStatus="holotype">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:D929AD541944C537FAA9FB11FB25FECE:545F4A991944C536F97EF9FDFCEEF986" box="[806,857,1575,1597]" country="Madagascar" county="We" municipality="Ankarafantsika forest" name="This" pageId="40" pageNumber="539" stateProvince="Mahajanga">This</location>
species was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Freytag PH &amp; Cwikla PS" pageId="40" pageNumber="539" pagination="341 - 344" refId="ref27098" refString="Freytag PH, Cwikla PS. 1984. Two new species of idiocerine leafhoppers from Malagasy Republic (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). The Pan-Pacific Entomologist 60: 341 - 344." type="journal article" year="1984">Freytag &amp; Cwikla (1984)</bibRefCitation>
based on a single male specimen from 
<collectingMunicipality box="[806,1058,1636,1658]" pageId="40" pageNumber="539">Ankarafantsika forest</collectingMunicipality>
reserve in the 
<collectingRegion country="Madagascar" name="Mahajanga" pageId="40" pageNumber="539">Mahajanga province</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[894,1034,1667,1689]" name="Madagascar" pageId="40" pageNumber="539">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. 
<collectingCounty box="[1048,1083,1667,1688]" pageId="40" pageNumber="539">We</collectingCounty>
could not examine the 
<typeStatus pageId="40" pageNumber="539">holotype</typeStatus>
as it is apparently lost. We identified this species in the present samples based on the similarity of both external morphology and genitalia characters. Pygofer, subgenital plate, style, connective, and shape of aedeagus are the same as in original description. The only difference we noticed is in the number of aedeagal processes. Aedeagus in lateral view has two pairs of lateral apical processes and a single process arising on ventral surface of shaft subapically. In the original description, the presence of this single subapical process is not mentioned or illustrated and we assume that this process might have broken off in the original specimen
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
